cell of the University to be appointed by the Board of Governors on the recommendations of
Selection Board on such terms and conditions, as may be prescribed.
(2) The minimum experience as well as the professional and academic qualifications
necessary for the appointment to the post of director quality enhancement cell shall be as may be
prescribed.
(3) The director quality enhancement cell shall be responsible to―
(i)     review the quality standards and the quality of teaching and learning in each
subject area;
(ii)    review the academic association with other institutions in terms of effective
management of standards and quality of programs;
(iii)    defining clear and explicit standards as points of reference to the review to be
carried out. It should also help the employees to know as to what they could
expect from candidates;
(iv)     developing qualifications framework by setting out the attributes and abilities
that can be expected from the holder of a qualification, i.e., undergraduate and
graduate programs;
(v)      developing program specifications. These are standards set of information
clarifying what knowledge, understanding, skills and other attributes a
student shall have developed on successfully completing a specific program;
(vi)     developing quality assurance processes and methods of evaluation to affirm
that the quality of provision and the standard of awards are being maintained
and to foster curriculum, subject, and staff development together with
research and other scholarly activities;
(vii)    ensure that the University’s quality assurance procedures are designed to fit
in with the arrangements in place nationally and internationally for
maintaining and improving the quality of Higher Education;
(viii)   developing procedures and processes, monitoring and evaluation systems,
and standards for the following―
(a)     approval of new program;
(b)     annual monitoring and evaluation including program monitoring,
faculty monitoring and student perceptions;
(c)     Departmental review;
(d)     Student feedback;
(e)     Employer feedback;
(f)     Quality assurance of undergraduate, graduate and doctoral programs;
(g)     Institutional assessment and performance evaluation;
(h)     Program specifications; and
(i)     Qualification framework.
(4) The director quality enhancement cell shall be the member of all statutory bodies and
committees of the University.
(5) The board of Governors may on the recommendations or advice of Vice-Chancellor,
terminate the services of the director quality enhancement cell on grounds of inefficiency or
misconduct in accordance with the prescribed procedure.

(i)   Authorities established by this Act—
(a)    The Board of Governors; and
(b)    The Academic Council.
(ii)   Authorities to be established by the Statutes:—
(a)     The Boards of Faculties;
(b)     The Board of Advanced Studies and Research;
(c)     The Board of Studies;
(d)     The Selection Board;
(e)     The Finance and Planning Committee;
(f)     Search Committee for the appointment of Vice-Chancellor;
(g)     Quality assurance Committee;
(h)     Discipline Committee; and
(i)     Such other authorities as may be prescribed.

provisions of this Act, and the statutes, exercise general supervision over the affairs and management
of the University.
(2) Without prejudice to the generality of the foregoing powers, the Board shall have the
following powers and functions―
(a)    to approve the proposed annual plan of work, the annual and revised budgets,
the annual statement of accounts and the annual report;
(b)    to hold, control and lay down policy for the registration of the property, finds,
assets, resources and investments of the University including the approval
of the sale and purchase or acquisition of immovable property;
(c)     to approve financial resource development plans of the University;
(d)    to oversee the quality and relevance of the University’s academic
programs and to review the academic affairs of the University in general;
(e)    to approve the appointment of the Deans, Chairperson of the teaching
departments, Professors, Associate Professors, Assistant Professors and such
other faculty members and officers, on the recommendations of the Selection
Board as may be prescribed;
(f)    to appoint Professor Emeritus on such terms and conditions as may be
prescribed;
(g)    to appoint the members of academic council, on the recommendations of the
Vice-Chancellor;
(h)    to institute schemes, directions and guidelines for the terms and conditions of
appointment of all officers, teachers and other employees of the University;
(i)    to approve strategic plans;
(j)    to consider and pass the draft Regulations, proposed by the Academic Council:
Provided that the Board of Governors may frame a Statute or Regulation on its
own initiative and approve it after calling for the advice of the Academic Council as
the case my be;
(k)      to make Statutes and revise them from time to time for the efficient and
effective operation of the university;
(l)    to annul by order in writing the proceedings of any Authority or officer if
the Board is satisfied that such proceedings are not in accordance with the
provisions of this Act, Statutes or Regulations after calling upon such
Authority or officer to show cause why such proceedings should not be
annulled;
(m)    to recommend to the Chancellor removal of any member of the Board of
Governors in accordance with the provisions of this Act;
(n)     to suspend, punish and remove employee (s) from service of the
University whom it is empowered to appoint in the manner prescribed after
due enquiry process;
(o)    to remove any person from the membership of any Authority, if such
person:―
(i)     has become of unsound mind; or
(ii)     has become incapacitated to function as member of such Authority;
or
(iii)   has been convicted by a court of law for an offence involving moral
turpitude; or
(iv)    has been found indulging in any activity against the interest of the
University;
(p)    to determine the form, provide for the custody and regulate the use of the
common seal of the University;
(q)    to hold, control and administer the property and funds and resources of the
University and raise funds upon such security as may be required under
Regulations;
(r)    to formulate or approve the principles, policies and plans governing the
activities and operations of the University so as to facilitate teaching, research
and other academic work;
(s)    to create such faculties, departments and institutes and to constitute such
standing committees, committees, sub-committees, councils and other
administrative or academic advisory bodies as it deems necessary, and review
their work;
(t)    to create such academic and administrative posts as it may deem necessary
and to suspend and abolish such posts;
(u)    to approve, carryout, vary or cancel contracts on behalf of the University;
(v)    to initiate and approve schemes for achievements of the objectives of the
University;
(w)    to determine the form, and regulate the custody and use common seal of the
University; and
(x)    to take such initiatives as it may consider necessary for the efficient and
effective management and functioning of the University.
(3) The Board may, subject to the provisions of this Act delegate all or any of the powers
and functions of any Authority, officer or employee of the University at its main campus, to any
Authority, committee, officer or employee at its additional campus for the purpose of exercising such
powers and performing such functions in relation to such additional campus, and for this purpose the
Board of Governors may create new posts or positions at the additional campus.

body of the University. The Academic Council shall consist of the following:―
(a)    the Vice-Chancellor who shall be its Chairperson;
(b)    Pro Vice-Chancellor (Academic and Research);
(c)    Pro Vice-Chancellor (Admin and Finance);
(d)    the Deans of Faculties;
(e)    the Chairpersons of Teaching Departments;
(f )   Heads of the Campuses and Constituent colleges or institutes;
(g)    five Professors including Emeritus Professors;
(h)    one nominee of HEC not below the rank of Director General;
(i)    one nominee of PM and DC
(j)    two eminent scholars to be nominated by the Board;
(k)    two persons of eminence to be nominated by the Chancellor;
(l)    the Controller of Examinations;
(m)    the Director QEC;
(n)    the Director ORIC;
(o)    the Controller of Examinations; and
(p)    the Registrar who shall act as its Secretary.
(2) The Members of the Academic Council shall hold office for three years.
(3) The Academic Council shall meet at least once in each quarter.
(4) The quorum for meetings of the Academic Council shall be one half of the total number
of members, a fraction being counted as one.

be the principal Academic Body of the University and shall, subject to provision of this Act and
Statutes, have the powers to lay down proper standards of instructions, research, publications, and
examinations, and to regulate, and promote academic life of the University.
(2) Without prejudice to the generality of the foregoing powers and provisions of this Act
and Statues, the Academic Council have the powers to―
(a)     advice the Board on academic matters;
(b)     lay down proper standards of instructions, research and examinations and
to regulate and promote the academic activities of the University;
(c)     regulate the conduct of teaching, research publications and examinations;
(d)     approve the policies and procedures pertaining to student-related functions
including admissions, expulsions, punishments, examinations and
certification;
(e)     approve academic programs and the policies and procedures pertaining to
the quality of academic programs;
(f)     approve the    policies and procedures assuring quality of teaching        and
research;
(g)      propose the Board, schemes for the constitution and organization of faculties,
teaching departments, colleges or institutes and Board of studies;
(h)     appoint paper setters and examiners for all examinations of the University
after receiving panels of names from the relevant authorities;
(i)     institute University programs for the continued professional development of
University Teachers at all levels;
(J)     recognize the examinations of other universities or examining bodies as
equivalent to the corresponding examinations of the University;
(k)     regulate the award of studentships, scholarships, exhibitions, medals and
prizes;
(l)     frame regulations for submission to Board;
(m)     make regulations for the constitution of faculties and the teaching
departments;
(n)     prepare an annual report on the academic performance of the University;
(o)    regulate the conduct and discipline of students and faculty;
(p)    frame regulations on the recommendations of the Board of Faculties and the
Boards of Studies, prescribing the courses of studies, and the syllabi for all
University examinations in accordance with the policy of HEC or PM and
DC and other regulatory bodies;
(q)    regulate the admissions of students to the courses of studies and examinations
in the University;
(r)    formulate proposals, for the planning and development of teaching and
research in the University;
(s)    recognize the examinations of other universities or examining bodies as
equivalent to corresponding examinations of the University; and
(t)    perform such functions as may be prescribed by Statutes or regulations.

